08699nam a22010335i 9781787448360DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a2020301419  a97817874483607 a10.1515/97817874483602doi  a(DE-B1597)677056  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK00aDA158b.C73 2020 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a942.018109200aConquests in Eleventh-Century England: 1016, 1066 /ced. by Laura Ashe, Emily Ward. 1aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (440 p.) :b1 colour, 12 b/w, 8 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tList of Illustrations -- tAbbreviations -- tI CONQUESTS, KINGS AND GOVERNMENT -- t1 Why 1016 Matters; or, The Politics of Memory and Identity in Cnut’s Kingdom -- t2 Why Did Cnut Conquer England? -- t3 Conquest and the Law -- t4 Cnut and William: A Comparison -- t5 Currency and Conquest in Eleventh-Century England -- t6 Episcopal Exon? Exeter, Cathedral Library, MS 3500 and the Role of Bishops in the Domesday Survey -- tII CONQUESTS, SOCIETY AND CULTURE -- t7 Conquest and Manuscript Culture -- t8 Kings, Saints and Conquests -- t9 Cultures of Conquest: Warfare and Enslavement in Britain Before and After 1066 -- t10 Conquest and Material Culture -- t11 Remapping Literary History: The Patronage of English Queens across the Norman Conquest -- t12 Queens and Demons: Women in English Royal Genealogies, c. 1100–c. 1223 -- t13 French Women in Early Norman England: The Case of Hawise of Bacqueville -- tIII CONQUESTS: PERSPECTIVES FROM BEYOND ENGLAND -- t14 English Contact with the European Mainland Throughout the Eleventh Century -- t15 The View from Wales: Anglo-Welsh Relations in the Time of England’s Conquests -- t16 England and the Papacy Between Two Conquests: The Shadow of ‘Reform' -- t17 Child Kings and the Norman Conquest: Representations of Association and Succession -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe cataclysmic conquests of the eleventh century are here set together for the first time.Eleventh-century England suffered two devastating conquests, each bringing the rule of a foreign king and the imposition of a new regime. Yet only the second event, the Norman Conquest of 1066, has been credited with the impact and influence of a permanent transformation. Half a century earlier, the Danish conquest of 1016 had nonetheless marked the painful culmination of decades of raiding and invasion - and more importantly, of centuries of England's conflict and cooperation with the Scandinavian world - and the Normans themselves were a part of that world. Without 1016, the conquest of 1066 could never have happened as it did: and yet disciplinary fragmentation in the study of eleventh-century England has ensured that a gulf separates the conquests in modern scholarship. The essays in this volume offer multidisciplinary perspectives on a century of conquest: in politics, law, governance, and religion; in art, literature, economics, and culture; and in the lives and experiences of peoples in a changing, febrile, and hybrid society. Crucially, it moves beyond an insular perspective, placing England within its British, Scandinavian, and European contexts; and in reaching across conquests connects the tenth century and earlier with the twelfth century and beyond, seeing the continuities in England's Anglo-Saxon, Danish, Norman, and Angevin elite cultureand rulership. The chapters break new ground in the documentary evidence and give fresh insights into the whole historical landscape, whilst fully engaging with the importance, influence, and effects of England's eleventh-centuryconquests, both separately and together. LAURA ASHE is Professor of English Literature and Fellow and Tutor in English, Worcester College, Oxford; EMILY JOAN WARD is Moses and Mary Finley Research Fellow, Darwin College, Cambridge. Contributors: Timothy Bolton, Stephanie Mooers Christelow, Julia Crick, Sarah Foot, John Gillingham, Charles Insley, Catherine Karkov, Lois Lane, Benjamin Savill, Peter Sigurdson Lunga, Niels Lund, Rory Naismith, Bruce O'Brien, Rebecca Thomas, Elizabeth M. Tyler, Elisabeth van Houts, Emily Joan Ward.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAssandun, Battle of, England, 1016. 0aHastings, Battle of, England, 1066. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCnut.  aDanish conquest.  aEngland.  aHastings.  aNorman Conquest.  aSwein.  aVikings.  aWilliam the Conqueror.  acurrency.  aeleventh century.  ainvasion.  akings.  amanuscripts.  amedieval.  anumismatics.  asaints.  aslavery.1 aAshe, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAshe, Laura, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBolton, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristelow, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrick, Julia C, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrick, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoot, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGillingham, John B, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGillingham, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHouts, Elisabeth van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInsley, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoan Ward, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarkov, Catherine